Early identification, early diagnosis and early isolation are the keys to avoiding community outbreaks. "To effectively reduce community transmission, greater efforts should be made to reduce social contact and urge people to cancel social activities and avoid going to crowded places, " Lin zhengyuee said

By Jiao Jian, special correspondent, Caijing

Editor | Susie

A flight originally scheduled to arrive in Hong Kong from Beijing at around 11:30 pm on February 7 was delayed until about 1 am on February 8. According to the new quarantine regulations promulgated by the Government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China on February 5, starting from midnight on February 8, people entering the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region from the mainland, including Hong Kong, mainland residents and other visitors, will be subject to mandatory quarantine for 14 days.

Behind the introduction of the policy, hong Kong, China (HKSAR) Government Chief Executive, Carrie Lam, said at a press conference on February 5 that patients with newly confirmed cases had no travel history during the incubation period, no apparent source of infection was found. This is a local case.

The passengers on the aforementioned flights should be counted as the first to be quarantined after the implementation of the policy. Under the sunset provisions, the regulation will expire at midnight on May 7 this year.

As the COVID-19 epidemic continues to spread across the country and the number of confirmed cases continues to increase, the government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China is stepping up its epidemic prevention measures. The main thrust of the plan is to continue to reduce cross-boundary flows between Hong Kong and the mainland, and to strengthen and improve the preparedness of the healthcare system.

However, due to the "neighborhood effect" caused by the quarantine center facilities and other factors, Hong Kong's overall anti-epidemic pressure is still not easy.

Quarantine reduces risk of infection

As of 12 noon on February 8, the total number of confirmed COVID-19 infections in the Hong Kong SAR of China had increased to 26, with one death.

On February 7, there were two more confirmed cases in Hong Kong: A 58-year-old man who worked in Zhuhai and Macau had taken a taxi to a private clinic and a North District Hospital clinic after returning to Hong Kong, a 42-year-old man from Prince of Wales Hospital was also confirmed infected late at night.

According to a previous analysis by the Centre for Health Protection, among the confirmed cases in Hong Kong as of February 5, there were 11 imported cases, 2 cases with close contact with imported cases, 3 cases with possible local infection and 5 cases with local infection.

Early identification, early diagnosis and early isolation are the keys to avoiding community outbreaks. "To effectively reduce community transmission, greater efforts should be made to reduce social contact and urge people to cancel social activities and avoid going to crowded places, " Lin zhengyuee said.

Whether there will be a large-scale outbreak in the next week or two in crowded public areas such as shopping malls and residential areas is also widely regarded as one of the core points of the current epidemic prevention and control in the Hong Kong SAR of China.

"At present, the focus of attention is not whether there has been community transmission in Hong Kong, but how big the transmission will be in the future, " a medical researcher from a Hong Kong University told Caijing, it's hard to find the source of the community.

As the maximum incubation period of COVID-19 is 14 days, how to implement the policy of 14 days quarantine in order to maximize the effect of disease prevention and control is the focus of attention.

Hong Kong residents who have been quarantined may be quarantined at home, during which they are not allowed to leave Hong Kong, while their families are not required to be quarantined, Food and Health Bureau, head of the government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China, said on February 7 Non-hong Kong residents who have arranged to stay in hotels or other accommodation will be quarantined there. If they can not, they will be quarantined in government-arranged facilities. The Hong Kong SAR Government of China will distribute "information packs" to visitors, providing information on personal and environmental hygiene.

Zheng Zhongwei, deputy secretary general (food) of the Food and Health Bureau, said: If the visa for entry is less than 14 days, the person will be refused entry, random checks will be arranged and contacts will be made by phone. No need to put on an electronic bracelet to monitor their whereabouts. Upon arrival in Hong Kong, they can travel by car to their residence.

To ensure the effectiveness of the quarantine, the above-mentioned new policy requires persons undergoing home quarantine to arrive at the designated place within two hours. The police will conduct random checks by telephone, WHATSAPP or visiting their homes. Those who can not be located will inform the Department of Health, the Department of Health will issue a quarantine order for the third time after the two warnings have lapsed.

Hong Kong residents who have visited Hubei Province in the past 14 days must be quarantined at home and wear electronic tracking bracelets, CAIJING reported earlier. Offenders are liable to a maximum penalty of six months'imprisonment and a fine of $5,000. More than 60 people are currently under quarantine.

The home quarantine, which began on February 8, is still relatively relaxed compared with the way in which bracelets are required. Matthew Cheung, the Chief Secretary of the Hong Kong SAR government, urged quarantine victims to "fully co-operate and exercise self-discipline in the spirit of social awareness and civic responsibility" .

According to a Hong Kong resident who had previously been subjected to similar quarantine at home for infectious disease, he was given quarantine notice after being diagnosed with chickenpox in a private clinic and then quarantined himself at home, told Caijing, during the relevant checks received telephone, "the whole process is relatively loose, but really depends on personal awareness. "

In accordance with the subsidiary rules of the mandatory quarantine regulations for certain arrivals made by the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region government at its special meeting on 7 February to amend the subsidiary legislation of the Prevention and Control of Disease Ordinance, offenders are liable to a maximum fine of $25,000(the same below) and six months'imprisonment.

The contours of the immune system are beginning to emerge

With the establishment and improvement of the above-mentioned systems to reduce customs clearance numbers and enhance quarantine, the broad outlines of the anti-epidemic systems in Hong Kong, China, are becoming clear in the light of the COVID-19 transmission:

According to the "preparedness and Response Plan for New Infectious Diseases of public health importance to the government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region" published in January 2020, to ensure that the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region government, to prevent, detect, control and respond to new infectious disease threats in a rapid, efficient and coordinated manner, thereby reducing deaths or morbidity. The plan comprises three response levels, namely alert, serious and emergency. The current response level for the COVID-19 is emergency.

According to Caijing reporters, the people involved in the current disease control and epidemic prevention system in the Hong Kong SAR may be divided into the following categories: ordinary citizens, susceptible groups, infected persons, suspected cases, those who had close contact with the infected person but had no symptoms of infection.

For Susceptible groups, the Department of Health of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region government of China Centre for Health Protection "Severe Emerging Infectious Agent Respiratory System Disease" , according to relevant information: from January 2 this year, the Centre has issued reminder letters to kindergartens / child care centres, schools, residential care homes for the elderly, residential care homes for the disabled and hospitals.

In a letter issued to kindergartens / Child Care Centres and schools on 2 January entitled "outbreak alert on Wuhan pneumonia clusters in Mainland" , "We are writing to alert you to a cluster of pneumonia cases in Wuhan, Hubei Province, which are being closely monitored by the DH's Centre for Health Protection, " the centre said. According to available information, a total of 27 pneumonia cases were reported in Wuhan in December 2019. The cases were related to a local seafood market, south China Seafood City, as at December 31. Seven cases are in serious condition while the rest are stable. The symptoms of the case were mainly fever with dyspnea in a few patients. All patients have been treated under isolation. Wuhan Health Authorities are tracking close contacts and putting them under medical observation. Experts in Wuhan have concluded that the case is viral pneumonia. At present, the detection of pathogens and the cause of infection is still under investigation. Students or staff of Your School / Institution should wear face masks and seek medical advice immediately if they develop fever or respiratory tract infection symptoms. They should also report their travel history and exposure history to doctors. Symptomatic students or staff should not return to school or work."

In addition to the relevant guidelines, the attached letter also contains relevant preventive advice. From 2 January to 8 February, about 30 similar letters in Chinese and English were sent to the different targets mentioned above. It covers the latest developments, measures to be implemented, and measures to be taken to enhance the response level.

According to the current medical arrangements in Hong Kong, all hospitals in each cluster are equipped with negative pressure isolation wards, trained healthcare staff and laboratory support to handle confirmed cases. Under the enhanced surveillance programme, patients who require laboratory testing will first be admitted to the negative pressure ward for isolation. However, as the number of cases increases, patients may be admitted to the ward for isolation. There will be a 1-metre distance between the beds in the ward and the bed for ventilation at least six times per hour, air Filtration equipment will be installed and full protective clothing will be worn to reduce nosocomial infection.

For those who have been confirmed to have been infected, according to the contingency plan of the Ha in the Hong Kong SAR, China, currently confirmed patients in Hong Kong will be sent to the Infectious Disease Centre of the Princess Margaret Hospital for treatment, confirmed patients will be admitted to the major acute hospitals in the seven hospital clusters. The chief manager (infection and emergency services) of the Hospital Authority, Zhuang Huimin, said each cluster could take in 20 confirmed patients and any more would be redeployed.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Hong Kong's current newly diagnosed patients will be sent to the Princess Margaret Hospital location. Photograph by Chiao Kin

At about 10 am on February 6, Caijing reporters found the hospital on a higher elevation, next to the Kwai Tsing Container Terminals, outside the Princess Margaret Hospital in Hong Kong's Kwai Chung District. With the exception of a small number of ambulances entering and leaving the hospital, there are few pedestrians in the vicinity and few people going to and from the hospital.

New Quarantine centres in full swing

Apart from the above home isolation and health care arrangements, the establishment of quarantine centres for those who have had close contact with confirmed patients but remain asymptomatic is another core challenge facing the HKSAR in the fight against the disease.

Previously, the HKSAR government has arranged for the Lady maclehose Holiday Village, the Lei Yue Mun Park Holiday village and the Pak Tam Chung Holiday Camp to be turned into quarantine centres. According to "CAIJING" reporters understand: the three places can provide a total of 97 independent quarantine units, as of February 5,80 have been used.

To increase the number of quarantine units, the HKSAR government is currently taking the initiative to contact various holiday camps. However, limited by geographical location, the limited number of individual rooms and other constraints, the current slow progress. In addition, the HKSAR government has also announced that it will commandeer the Jao Tsung-i Academy in Lai Chi Kok as the fourth quarantine centre in Hong Kong.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Hong Kong has announced that it will commandeer the Tsui Nga Shan House in the Jao Tsung-i Academy as the city's Fourth Quarantine Centre. Photograph by Chiao Kin

The JAO Tsung-i Academy is located at 800 Castle Peak Road, Lai Chi Kok, Kowloon, Hong Kong. These three-grade historic buildings in Hong Kong have experienced the functions of "Kowloon Pass" , "pig house" , prison and hospital. There are currently 89 rooms in the Cuiya Mountain House, which serves as a hotel.

The Food and Health Bureau in the Hong Kong SAR of China has previously pointed out that the Jao Tsung-i Academy is located on a hill and its overall facilities meet the requirements. Among them, the Tsui Nga Shan House was built for medical purposes. The partitions and facilities are suitable for use as a quarantine centre. It is also relatively far from residential areas. It is the fastest facility to be converted into a Quarantine Centre for service. Once the centre is opened, law enforcement officers and medical staff will be on hand 24 hours a day to monitor the situation. Those who flee will be held accountable.

On the morning of February 6, Caijing reporters found outside the Jao Tsung-i Academy: The area has been temporarily closed and is no longer open to the public, there are also corresponding administrators in the courtyard for inspection.

According to people familiar with the matter told CAIJING: "This is Hong Kong's diagnosis and treatment of leprosy patients, geographical location and residential distance. ". However, residents of Mei Foo Sun Chuen, which is only one road away from the cultural centre, told Caijing that the hill houses are too close to residential buildings to be used for isolating suspected cases, and it would be acceptable if they were only used for isolation accommodation for medical staff.

The Sham Shui Po District Council held a special meeting on February 5 to discuss measures in response to protests from nearby residents. At the meeting, a motion opposing the use of the Cuiya Hill House as an isolation camp was put forward, the result of the vote was 22 in favour and 2 abstentions.

Earlier, the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) government had proposed to set aside a building at Fai Ming estate in Fanling as an isolation centre, but the proposal could not be implemented due to various reasons. In contrast, another Hong Kong Chinese Medicine Hospital, which was considered a candidate site by public opinion, has been deserted for several years, it's GonNa be hard to get it up and running any time soon. Although the Development Bureau of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region is also studying the possibility of finding vacant land to build additional quarantine centre facilities, it can not be put into use in the near future.

To increase the number of quarantine centers, Disney could commandeer three hotels and even consider using part of the Shek Kong military barracks, Henry Tang, president of the Standing Committee of the National Committee of the CPPCC and the Hong Kong friendship and Promotion Council, said on February 5 when making recommendations on the fight against the disease.

The latest news is that the government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China is at full speed to prepare for the addition of quarantine units in the form of modular housing in the three existing quarantine centres and Sai Kung outdoor recreation centre. The first batch of 100 flats can be completed by mid-march at the earliest.
